## 2. One-Rep Max (1RM) Estimation Formulas

Convert any "weight × reps" set into an estimated single-rep max. Implement several and let the
user choose (or average them). `w` = weight lifted, `r` = reps performed.

| Formula | Equation | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| **Epley** | `1RM = w × (1 + r / 30)` | Most common; good general use |
| **Brzycki** | `1RM = w × 36 / (37 − r)` | Accurate for low reps (<10) |
| **Lander** | `1RM = (100 × w) / (101.3 − 2.67123 × r)` | — |
| **Lombardi** | `1RM = w × r^0.10` | Power-curve based |
| **Mayhew et al.** | `1RM = (100 × w) / (52.2 + 41.9 × e^(−0.055 × r))` | Research-validated |
| **O'Conner et al.** | `1RM = w × (1 + 0.025 × r)` | Simple linear |
| **Wathan** | `1RM = (100 × w) / (48.8 + 53.8 × e^(−0.075 × r))` | — |

> If `r == 1`, 1RM = w (skip estimation).
> Accuracy degrades above ~10–12 reps for all formulas; warn the user.

**Reps → % of 1RM reference table** (standard, used to predict load for a target rep count):

| Reps | % 1RM | Reps | % 1RM | Reps | % 1RM |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | 100 | 11 | 73 | 21 | 59 |
| 2 | 97 | 12 | 71 | 22 | 58 |
| 3 | 94 | 13 | 70 | 23 | 57 |
| 4 | 92 | 14 | 68 | 24 | 56 |
| 5 | 89 | 15 | 67 | 25 | 55 |
| 6 | 86 | 16 | 65 | 26 | 54 |
| 7 | 83 | 17 | 64 | 27 | 53 |
| 8 | 81 | 18 | 63 | 28 | 52 |
| 9 | 78 | 19 | 61 | 29 | 51 |
| 10 | 75 | 20 | 60 | 30 | 50 |

**References:** Epley B. (1985); Brzycki M. (1993), *JOPERD*; Lombardi V.P. (1989);
Mayhew J.L. et al. (1992), *J. Appl. Sport Sci. Res.*

