## 7. Legal Open Data Sources (build standards from these)

| Source | What it gives you | License | Link |
|---|---|---|---|
| **OpenPowerlifting** | 2.5M+ verified squat/bench/deadlift competition results with bodyweight, sex, age | **Public domain** (data) / AGPLv3 (code) | https://data.openpowerlifting.org |
| OpenPowerlifting repo | Raw CSVs + checker code | AGPLv3+ | https://gitlab.com/openpowerlifting/opl-data |
| OpenWeight | Vendor-neutral JSON schema for logs/programs/profiles (import/export) | Open | https://github.com/radupana/openweight |
| Kaggle mirror | Convenient CSV snapshot of OpenPowerlifting | Public domain | https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/open-powerlifting/powerlifting-database |

**Recommended workflow to generate real percentiles:**
1. Download `openpowerlifting.csv`.
2. Filter by sex, equipment = Raw, valid bodyweight & lift values.
3. Bucket by bodyweight class (e.g. 5–10 kg bins).
4. For each (exercise, sex, bodyweight bin), compute the 5/20/50/80/95th percentiles of 1RM.
5. Export to a compact lookup table (JSON) the app ships with — no live API calls needed.
6. Add a one-line attribution: *"Includes data from OpenPowerlifting.org (public domain)."*

> OpenPowerlifting only covers squat/bench/deadlift. For accessory lifts not in the dataset,
> derive standards as a ratio of the nearest compound (e.g. incline bench ≈ 0.8 × flat bench;
> front squat ≈ 0.85 × back squat) and label them clearly as **estimates**.

